AWS VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) — Developer Guide
📌 What is a VPC?

A VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) is a private network inside AWS where you deploy and control your cloud resources.

It acts like your own data center network in the cloud.

Inside a VPC, you control:

IP address ranges
Subnets
Internet access
Security rules
Routing
Resource isolation
=============================================================
🏗 High Level Architecture
AWS Region
   └── VPC (Private Network)
           ├── Public Subnet
           └── Private Subnet
=========================================================================
All AWS services such as EC2, RDS, Load Balancers run inside a VPC.

🧠 Real World Analogy
Real World	AWS Equivalent
City	AWS Region
Gated Community	VPC
Streets	Subnets
Houses	EC2 Instances
Security Gate	Internet Gateway
===============================================================
Core VPC Concepts
1️⃣ CIDR Block (IP Address Range)

Defines IP address range for the VPC.

Example:

10.0.0.0/16

Meaning:

Private network
Supports ~65,536 IP addresses

Example subnet ranges:

10.0.1.0/24
10.0.2.0/24
=========================================================================
2️⃣ Subnets

A Subnet is a smaller network inside a VPC.

Public Subnet
Connected to internet
Used for:
Load Balancer
Bastion Host
Public servers
Private Subnet
No direct internet access
Used for:
Backend services
Databases
Example
VPC
 ├── Public Subnet
 │       └── Load Balancer
 │
 └── Private Subnet
         ├── Spring Boot EC2
         └── RDS Database
========================================================
3️⃣ Internet Gateway (IGW)

Allows communication between VPC and the Internet.

Without Internet Gateway:

No inbound or outbound internet traffic.
Internet <--> Internet Gateway <--> VPC
======================================================================
4️⃣ Route Tables

Defines how network traffic flows.

Example Route:

Destination      Target
0.0.0.0/0        Internet Gateway

Meaning:
All external traffic goes to the internet.

Each subnet must be associated with a Route Table.
=====================================================================================

5️⃣ NAT Gateway

Allows private subnet resources to access internet securely.

Used when:

Servers need updates
External API calls
Package installations
Private EC2 → NAT Gateway → Internet

✔ Outbound internet allowed
❌ No inbound internet access
===========================================================================

6️⃣ Security Groups (Instance Firewall)

Security Groups act as a firewall for EC2 instances.

Example Rules:

Inbound:
Port 22   → SSH Access
Port 80   → HTTP
Port 8080 → Spring Boot

Outbound:
Allow All

Characteristics:

Instance level
Stateful
Most commonly used security control
==============================================================
7️⃣ Network ACL (NACL)

Subnet-level firewall.

Feature	Security Group	NACL
Level	Instance	Subnet
Stateful	Yes	No
Usage	Common	Rare

Developers mostly work with Security Groups.
=========================================================================

🧑‍💻 How Developers Use VPC

Typical Java Full Stack Deployment:

Step 1 — Create VPC
CIDR: 10.0.0.0/16
Step 2 — Create Subnets
Subnet	Type	Purpose
Subnet A	Public	Load Balancer
Subnet B	Private	Spring Boot Backend
Subnet C	Private	Database
Step 3 — Attach Internet Gateway

Enable public access.

Step 4 — Configure NAT Gateway

Allow private backend servers internet access safely.

Step 5 — Deploy Application
Frontend
React hosted on S3
Backend
Spring Boot deployed on EC2 (Private Subnet)
Database
RDS inside Private Subnet
🏗 Production Architecture (3-Tier Architecture)
Users
  ↓
Application Load Balancer (Public Subnet)
  ↓
Spring Boot EC2 (Private Subnet)
  ↓
RDS Database (Private Subnet)

